Blood pressure is usually classified based on the systolic and diastolic blood pressures. Systolic blood pressure is the blood pressure in vessels during a heart beat. Diastolic blood pressure is the pressure between heartbeats. A systolic or the diastolic blood pressure measurement higher than the accepted normal values for the age of the individual is classified as prehypertension or hypertension.

Hypertension<ref name="High blood pressure">{{cite web | title = High blood pressure - NHS | url = http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/Blood-pressure-(high)/Pages/Introduction.aspx | publisher = [[National Health Service (NHS)]]}}</ref> has several sub-classifications including, hypertension stage I, hypertension stage II, and isolated systolic hypertension. Isolated systolic hypertension refers to elevated systolic pressure with normal diastolic pressure and is common in the elderly. These classifications are made after averaging a patient's resting blood pressure readings taken on two or more office visits. Individuals older than 50 years are classified as having hypertension if their blood pressure is consistently at least 140&nbsp;mmHg systolic or 90&nbsp;mmHg diastolic. Patients with blood pressures higher than 130/80&nbsp;mmHg with concomitant presence of [[diabetes mellitus]] or [[kidney disease]] require further treatment.<ref name="jnc7"/>

Hypertension is also classified as resistant if [[Pharmaceutical drug|medications]] do not reduce blood pressure to normal levels.<ref name="jnc7"/>

[[Exercise hypertension]] is an excessively high elevation in blood pressure during [[exercise]].<ref name="pmid3583204">{{cite journal |author=Jett<U+00E9> M, Landry F, Bl<U+00FC>mchen G |title=Exercise hypertension in healthy normotensive subjects. Implications, evaluation and interpretation |journal=[[Herz]] |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=110<U+2013>8 |year=1987 |month=April |pmid=3583204 |doi= |url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-20}}</ref><ref name="pmid2953661">{{cite journal |author=Pickering TG |title=Pathophysiology of exercise hypertension |journal=[[Herz]] |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=119<U+2013>24 |year=1987 |month=April |pmid=2953661 |doi= |url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-20}}</ref><ref name="pmid3583205">{{cite journal |author=Rost R, Heck H |title=[Exercise hypertension--significance from the viewpoint of sports] |language=German |journal=[[Herz]] |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=125<U+2013>33 |year=1987 |month=April |pmid=3583205 |doi= |url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-20}}</ref> The range considered normal for systolic values during exercise is between 200 and 230&nbsp;mm Hg.<ref name="pmid3583208">{{cite journal |author=Klaus D |title=[Differential therapy of exercise hypertension] |language=German |journal=[[Herz]] |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=146<U+2013>55 |year=1987 |month=April |pmid=3583208 |doi= |url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-20}}</ref> Exercise hypertension may indicate that an individual is at risk for developing hypertension at rest.<ref name="pmid3583205" /><ref name="pmid3583208"/>

==Signs and symptoms==
Mild to moderate essential hypertension is usually [[asymptomatic]].<ref name="pmid9472183">{{cite journal |author=Pitts SR, Adams RP |title=Emergency department hypertension and regression to the mean |journal=[[Annals of Emergency Medicine]] |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=214<U+2013>8 |year=1998 |month=February |pmid=9472183 |doi= 10.1016/S0196-0644(98)70309-9|url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-18}}</ref>

===Accelerated hypertension===
Accelerated hypertension is associated with [[headache]], [[somnolence|drowsiness]], [[confusion]], [[vision disorder]]s, [[nausea]], and [[vomiting]]. These symptoms are collectively called [[hypertensive encephalopathy]].<ref name="Oppenheimer and Fishberg 1928">Oppenheimer, B S, and Fishberg, A M, Archives of Internal Medicine, 1928, 41, 264.</ref> Hypertensive encephalopathy is caused by severe [[capillary|small blood vessel]] congestion and [[cerebral edema|brain swelling]], which is reversible if blood pressure is lowered.<ref name="isbn0-07-159124-9">{{cite book |author=Papadakis, Maxine A.; McPhee, Stephen J. |authorlink= |editor= |others= |title=Current Medical Diagnosis and Treatment 2009 (Current Medical Diagnosis and Treatment) |edition= |language= |publisher=McGraw-Hill Professional |location= |year=2008 |origyear= |pages= |quote= |isbn=0-07-159124-9 |oclc= }}</ref>

===Secondary hypertension===
{{Main|Secondary hypertension}}
Some additional signs and symptoms suggest that the hypertension is caused by disorders in hormone regulation. Hypertension combined with [[centripetal obesity|obesity distributed on the trunk of the body]], accumulated fat on the back of the neck ('[[lipodystrophy|buffalo hump]]'), wide purple marks on the abdomen ([[abdominal striae]]), or the recent onset of diabetes suggests that an individual has a hormone disorder known as [[Cushing's syndrome]]. Hypertension caused by other [[endocrine disease|hormone disorders]] such as [[hyperthyroidism]], [[hypothyroidism]], or [[growth hormone excess]] will be accompanied by additional symptoms specific to these disorders. For example, hyperthyrodism can cause [[weight loss]], [[tremors]], [[tachycardia|heart rate abnormalities]], [[palmar erythema|reddening of the palms]], and increased [[sweating]].<ref name="urlHyperthyroidism: eMedicine Endocrinology">{{cite web |url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/121865-overview |title=Hyperthyroidism |author=Lee, Stephanie L |authorlink= |coauthors=Ananthakrishnan, Sonia |date=April 26, 2010 |work=eMedicine Endocrinology |publisher=Medscape |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= |accessdate=2009-06-16}}</ref> Signs and symptoms associated with [[growth hormone excess]] include coarsening of facial features, [[prognathism|protrusion of the lower jaw]], [[macroglossia|enlargement of the tongue]],<ref name="urlAcromegaly: eMedicine Endocrinology">{{cite web |url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/116366-overview |title=Acromegaly |author=Khandwala, Hasnain M |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=February 13, 2009 |work=eMedicine Endocrinology |publisher=Medscape |pages= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= |accessdate=2009-06-16}}</ref> [[hypertrichosis|excessive hair growth]], [[hyperpigmentation|darkening of the skin color]], and [[hyperhidrosis|excessive sweating]].<ref name="Andrews">{{cite book |author=James, William; Berger, Timothy; Elston, Dirk |year=2005 |title=Andrews' Diseases of the Skin:no Clinical Dermatology |edition=10th |publisher=Saunders |isbn=0721629210}}</ref>{{Rp|499|date=May 2009}}. Other hormone disorders like [[hyperaldosteronism]] may cause less specific symptoms such as [[numbness]], [[polyuria|excessive urination]], [[polydipsia|excessive sweating]], [[hypernatraemia|electrolyte imbalances and dehydration]], and [[metabolic alkalosis|elevated blood alkalinity]].<ref name="urlHyperaldosteronism: eMedicine Pediatrics: General Medicine">{{cite web |url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/920713-overview |title=Hyperaldosteronism |work=eMedicine Pediatrics: General Medicine |author=Chrousos, George P |authorlink= |coauthors=Lafferty, Antony |date=March 4, 2009 |publisher=Medscape |pages= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= |accessdate=2009-06-16}}</ref> and also cause of mental pressure.

===In pregnancy===
Hypertension in pregnant women is one symptom of [[pre-eclampsia]]. Pre-eclampsia can progress to a life-threatening condition called [[eclampsia]], which is the development of [[proteinuria|protein in the urine]], [[edema|generalized swelling]], and severe [[tonic-clonic seizures|seizures]]. Other symptoms indicating that brain function is becoming impaired may precede these seizures such as nausea, vomiting, headaches, and [[blindness|vision loss]].<ref name="urlHypertension and Pregnancy: eMedicine Obstetrics and Gynecology">{{cite web |url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/261435-overview |title=Hypertension and Pregnancy |author=Gibson, Paul |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=July 30, 2009 |work=eMedicine Obstetrics and Gynecology |publisher=Medscape |pages= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate=2009-06-16}}</ref>

In addition, the systemic vascular resistance and blood pressure decrease during pregnancy. The body must compensate by increasing cardiac output and blood volume to provide sufficient circulation in the utero-placental arterial bed.<ref>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20954460</ref>

===In children===
Some signs and symptoms are especially important in [[neonates|newborns]] and [[infants]] such as [[failure to thrive]], [[seizures]], [[irritability]], [[lethargy|lack of energy]], and [[respiratory distress|difficulty breathing]].<ref name="urlHypertension: eMedicine Pediatrics: Cardiac Disease and Critical Care Medicine">{{cite web |url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/889877-overview |title=Hypertension |author=Rodriguez-Cruz, Edwin |authorlink= |coauthors=Ettinger, Leigh M |date=April 6, 2010 |work=eMedicine Pediatrics: Cardiac Disease and Critical Care Medicine |publisher=Medscape |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= |accessdate=2009-06-16}}</ref> In children, hypertension can cause headache, [[fatigue (medical)|fatigue]], [[blurred vision]], [[epistaxis|nosebleeds]], and [[bell palsy|facial paralysis]].<ref name="urlHypertension: eMedicine Pediatrics: Cardiac Disease and Critical Care Medicine"/>

Even with the above clinical symptoms, the true incidence of pediatric hypertension is not known. In adults, hypertension has been defined due to the adverse effects caused by hypertension. However, in children, similar studies have not been performed thoroughly to link any adverse effects with the increase in blood pressure. Therefore, the prevalence of pediatric hypertension remains unknown due to the lack of scientific knowledge.<ref>http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/889877-overview</ref>

==Causes==
===Essential hypertension===
{{Main|Essential hypertension}}
Essential hypertension is the most prevalent hypertension type, affecting 90<U+2013>95% of hypertensive patients.<ref name="pmid10645931"/> Although no direct cause has been identified, there are many factors such as [[sedentary lifestyle]],<ref name="pmid17148735">{{cite journal |author=Kyrou I, Chrousos GP, Tsigos C |title=Stress, visceral obesity, and metabolic complications |journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences |volume=1083 |issue= |pages=77<U+2013>110 |year=2006 |month=November |pmid=17148735 |doi=10.1196/annals.1367.008}}</ref> smoking, stress, visceral obesity, potassium deficiency ([[hypokalemia]]),<ref name="pmid17148735"/> [[obesity]]<ref name="pmid15579059">{{cite journal |doi=10.2174/1381612043382855 |author=Wofford MR, Hall JE |title=Pathophysiology and treatment of obesity hypertension |journal=Current Pharmaceutical Design |volume=10 |issue=29 |pages=3621<U+2013>37 |year=2004 |pmid=15579059 |url=http://www.bentham-direct.org/pages/content.php?CPD/2004/00000010/00000029/0007B.SGM}}</ref> (more than 85% of cases occur in those with a [[body mass index]] greater than 25),<ref name=HaslamJames>{{cite journal |author=Haslam DW, James WP |title=Obesity |journal=Lancet |volume=366 |issue=9492 |pages=1197<U+2013>209 |year=2005 |pmid=16198769 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(05)67483-1}}</ref> [[Salt#Health effects|salt (sodium) sensitivity]],<ref name="pmid17686383">{{cite journal |author=Lackland DT, Egan BM |title=Dietary salt restriction and blood pressure in clinical trials |journal=[[Curr. Hypertens. Rep.]] |volume=9 |issue=4 |pages=314<U+2013>9 |year=2007 |month=August |pmid=17686383 |doi= 10.1007/s11906-007-0057-8|url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref> [[alcohol]] intake,<ref name="pmid19480755">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S1885-5857(09)72223-6 |author=Djouss<U+00E9> L, Mukamal KJ |title=Alcohol consumption and risk of hypertension: does the type of beverage or drinking pattern matter? |journal=Revista Espa<U+00F1>ola De Cardiolog<U+00ED>a |volume=62 |issue=6 |pages=603<U+2013>5 |year=2009 |month=June |pmid=19480755 |url=http://www.revespcardiol.org/cardio/62/603}}</ref> and [[hypovitaminosis D|vitamin D deficiency]] that increase the risk of developing hypertension.<ref name="pmid19444937">{{cite journal |author=Tuohimaa P |title=Vitamin D and aging |journal=[[The Journal of Steroid Biochemistry and Molecular Biology]] |volume=114 |issue=1-2 |pages=78<U+2013>84 |year=2009 |month=March |pmid=19444937 |doi= 10.1016/j.jsbmb.2008.12.020|url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Lee JH, O'Keefe JH, Bell D, Hensrud DD, Holick MF |title=Vitamin D deficiency an important, common, and easily treatable cardiovascular risk factor? |journal=J. Am. Coll. Cardiol. |volume=52 |issue=24 |pages=1949<U+2013>56 |year=2008 |pmid=19055985 |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2008.08.050 }}</ref> Risk also increases with [[aging]],<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kosugi T, Nakagawa T, Kamath D, Johnson RJ |title=Uric acid and hypertension: an age-related relationship? |journal=J Hum Hypertens |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=75<U+2013>6 |year=2009 |month=February |pmid=18754017 |doi=10.1038/jhh.2008.110 |url=}}</ref> some inherited [[genetic mutations]],<ref name="pmid16754793">{{cite journal |author=Dickson ME, Sigmund CD |title=Genetic basis of hypertension: revisiting angiotensinogen |journal=Hypertension |volume=48 |issue=1 |pages=14<U+2013>20 |year=2006 |month=July |pmid=16754793 |doi=10.1161/01.HYP.0000227932.13687.60}}</ref> and having a family history of hypertension.<ref name="pmid16719248">{{cite journal |author=Luma GB, Spiotta RT |title=Hypertension in children and adolescents |journal=[[Am Fam Physician]] |volume=73 |issue=9 |pages=1558<U+2013>68 |year=2006 |month=May |pmid=16719248 |doi= |url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref> An elevated level of [[renin]], a hormone secreted by the kidney, is another risk factor,<ref name="pmid17903324">{{cite journal |author=Segura J, Ruilope LM |title=Obesity, essential hypertension and renin-angiotensin system |journal=Public Health Nutrition |volume=10 |issue=10A |pages=1151<U+2013>5 |year=2007 |month=October |pmid=17903324 |doi=10.1017/S136898000700064X}}</ref> as is [[sympathetic system|sympathetic]] nervous system overactivity.<ref name="hypertension9">{{cite journal |author=Rahmouni K, Correia ML, Haynes WG, Mark AL |title=Obesity-associated hypertension: new insights into mechanisms |journal=Hypertension |volume=45 |issue=1 |pages=9<U+2013>14 |year=2005 |month=January |pmid=15583075 |doi=10.1161/01.HYP.0000151325.83008.b4 |url=}}</ref> [[Insulin resistance]], which is a component of [[metabolic syndrome|syndrome X]] (or the [[metabolic syndrome]]), is also thought to contribute to hypertension.<ref name="pmid17903324"/><ref name="pmid12364344">{{cite journal |author=Sorof J, Daniels S |title=Obesity hypertension in children: a problem of epidemic proportions |journal=Hypertension |volume=40 |issue=4 |pages=441<U+2013>7 |year=2002 |month=October |pmid=12364344 |doi= 10.1161/01.HYP.0000032940.33466.12|url=http://hyper.ahajournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=12364344 |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-03}}</ref> Recent studies have implicated [[low birth weight]] as a risk factor for adult essential hypertension.<ref name="pmid18700545">{{cite journal |author=Uchiyama M |title=[Mild hypertension in children] |language=Japanese |journal=[[Nippon Rinsho]] |volume=66 |issue=8 |pages=1477<U+2013>80 |year=2008 |month=August |pmid=18700545 |doi= |url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref>

===Secondary hypertension===
{{Main|Secondary hypertension}}
Secondary hypertension by definition results from an identifiable cause. This type is important to recognize since it's treated differently to essential hypertension, by treating the underlying cause of the elevated blood pressure. Hypertension results in the compromise or imbalance of the pathophysiological mechanisms, such as the hormone-regulating [[endocrine]] system, that regulate blood plasma volume and heart function. Many conditions cause hypertension. Some are common, well-recognized secondary causes such as [[Cushing's syndrome]],<ref name="pmid19096817">{{cite journal |author=Dodt C, Wellh<U+00F6>ner JP, Sch<U+00FC>tt M, Sayk F |title=[Glucocorticoids and hypertension] |language=German |journal=[[Der Internist]] |volume=50 |issue=1 |pages=36<U+2013>41 |year=2009 |month=January |pmid=19096817 |doi=10.1007/s00108-008-2197-6 |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-18}}</ref> which is a condition where the [[adrenal gland]]s overproduce the hormone [[cortisol]].<ref name="pmid19096817"/> Hypertension is also caused by other conditions that cause hormone changes, such as hyperthyroidism, hypothyroidism (citation needed), and certain tumors of the adrenal medulla (e.g., [[pheochromocytoma]]). Other common causes of secondary hypertension include kidney disease, obesity/[[metabolic disorder]], [[pre-eclampsia]] during pregnancy, the congenital defect known as [[coarctation of the aorta]], and certain prescription and illegal drugs.

==Pathophysiology==
{{Main|Pathophysiology of hypertension}}
[[Image:Arterial pressure diagram.png|thumb|right|350px|A diagram explaining factors affecting [[arterial pressure]]]]
Most of the mechanisms associated with secondary hypertension are generally fully understood. However, those associated with [[essential (primary) hypertension]] are far less understood. What is known is that [[cardiac output]] is raised early in the disease course, with [[total peripheral resistance]] (TPR) normal; over time cardiac output drops to normal levels but TPR is increased. Three theories have been proposed to explain this:
* Inability of the kidneys to excrete sodium, resulting in [[natriuretic]] factors such as [[Atrial Natriuretic Factor]] being secreted to promote salt excretion with the [[side effect]] of raising total peripheral resistance.
* An overactive [[Renin-angiotensin system]] leads to [[vasoconstriction]] and retention of sodium and water. The increase in [[blood volume]] plus vasoconstriction leads to hypertension.<ref name="pmid19475781">{{cite journal |author=Pimenta E, Oparil S |title=Role of aliskiren in cardio-renal protection and use in hypertensives with multiple risk factors |journal=[[Vascular Health and Risk Management]] |volume=5 |issue=1 |pages=453<U+2013>63 |year=2009 |pmid=19475781 |pmc=2686262 |doi= |url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref>
* An overactive [[sympathetic nervous system]], leading to increased stress responses.<ref name="pmid18700548">{{cite journal |author=Takahashi H |title=[Sympathetic hyperactivity in hypertension] |language=Japanese |journal=[[Nippon Rinsho. Japanese Journal of Clinical Medicine]] |volume=66 |issue=8 |pages=1495<U+2013>502 |year=2008 |month=August |pmid=18700548 |doi= |url= |issn= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref>
It is also known that hypertension is highly heritable and [[polygenic]] (caused by more than one gene) and a few candidate [[genes]] have been postulated in the etiology of this condition.<ref name="polymorphism">{{cite journal |author= Sagnella GA, Swift PA |journal=Current Pharmaceutical Design |title=The Renal Epithelial Sodium Channel: Genetic Heterogeneity and Implications for the Treatment of High Blood Pressure |year = 2006 |month = June |volume = 12 |issue = 14 |pages = 2221<U+2013>2234 |pmid = 16787251 | doi = 10.2174/138161206777585157}}</ref>

Recently, work related to the association between essential hypertension and sustained endothelial damage has gained popularity among hypertension scientists. It remains unclear however whether endothelial changes precede the development of hypertension or whether such changes are mainly due to long standing elevated blood pressures.

==Diagnosis==
Hypertension is generally diagnosed on the basis of a persistently high blood pressure. Usually this requires three separate sphygmomanometer (see figure) measurements at least one week apart. Often, this entails three separate visits to the physician's office. Initial assessment of the hypertensive patient should include a complete [[Medical history|history]] and [[physical examination]]. Exceptionally, if the elevation is extreme, or if symptoms of organ damage are present then the diagnosis may be given and treatment started immediately.

Once the diagnosis of hypertension has been made, physicians will attempt to identify the underlying cause based on risk factors and other symptoms, if present. [[Secondary hypertension]] is more common in preadolescent children, with most cases caused by [[renal disease]]. Primary or [[essential hypertension]] is more common in adolescents and has multiple risk factors, including obesity and a family history of hypertension.<ref name="pmid16719248">{{cite journal | author = Luma GB, Spiotta RT | title = Hypertension in children and adolescents | journal = Am Fam Physician | volume = 73 | issue = 9 | pages = 1558<U+2013>68 | month = may | year = 2006 | pmid = 16719248}}</ref> Laboratory tests can also be performed to identify possible causes of secondary hypertension, and determine if hypertension has caused damage to the [[Human heart|heart]], [[Human eyes|eyes]], and [[kidney]]s. Additional tests for Diabetes and high [[cholesterol]] levels are also usually performed because they are additional risk factors for the development of [[heart disease]] require treatment.<ref name="pmid10645931"/> Tests typically performed are classified as follows:
